node.text:
The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is home to more than 200 species of birds and is sacred land for the Gwich'in people—but it has never been in greater danger. On the Arctic Refuge Day of Action, learn more about this vast Alaskan wilderness and what you can do to help protect this critical habitat.

Join us in taking action to #ProtectTheArctic today: https://www.audubon.org/arcticrefuge

node.title: Why Birds Need the Arctic Refuge

node.text:
Did you know that the Boreal Forest is home to between 1-3 billion birds that nest in the region each year? Not only that: it’s a nature based climate solution, holding about 12% of land-based carbon reserves. Audubon is working closely with our chapters, members, and Indigenous partners to protect one of the largest intact forests left on planet Earth. 🌲

On #WorldMigratoryBirdDay, learn more about conservation efforts for North America’s bird nursery: audubon.org/borealforests

node.title: The Boreal Forest: A Bird Haven

node.text:
Did you know that the Great Lakes provide drinking water to 40 million people and its coastal habitats support more than 350 bird species? As climate change, coastal development, and invasive species threaten these communities and habitats, @audubongreatlakes is ready with a bold plan.

Our new report, Restoring the Great Lakes for Birds and People, uses science to pinpoint the highest-priority coastal regions for birds, water quality, and coastal resiliency—focusing conservation where it’s needed most. Learn more and join us on this journey: https://bit.ly/397ppSG

node.title: Protecting Birds in the Great Lakes

The fierce and resilient Bald Eagle is a common sight today, but did you know the species was on the brink of extinction in the 1970s? Eagles recovered thanks to increased protections under the Endangered Species Act, but new rules would weaken it. 

Urge your members of Congress today to stand up for this critical law: https://bit.ly/3tjk9TH

node.title: How the Bald Eagle Made a Comeback

Then, tell Congress to take action to support cheatgrass control and sagebrush habitat restoration: http://audubon.org/cheatgrass

node.text: Audubon’s Seabird Institute works to restore Atlantic Puffin and other seabird populations to islands off the coast of Maine. Each summer, a team of research assistants live and conduct research on these islands. Listen in to learn about this experience. Want to apply to become a research assistant? Visit https://www.audubon.org/seabirdsummer

node.text: Swans made of broken glass and ceramic appear to fly out of a 20-foot mosaic on a corner in upper Manhattan—serving as both an inspiring addition to a community hit hard by COVID-19 and a sobering reminder that the species, after bouncing back from near extinction, is now threatened by climate change. Learn how artists Carlos Pinto (@pintocards) & John Sear created the 20-foot mural: https://bit.ly/2XL2dna #AudubonMuralProject

node.text:
This Yellow-headed Blackbird knows it’s better to stand out than to try fitting into the crowd. When Marti Phillips (@smartipix) photographed the solitary songbird at the Bosque Del Apache National Wildlife Refuge, she wondered if he was lost or separated from his flock. After returning home and reviewing the day’s photos, she spotted his trademark yellow feathers later in this sea of Red-winged blackbirds.⁠
⁠
The final shot shows the flock of Red-winged Blackbirds taking off from a cornfield. The birds in the foreground are in focus, their bright red wing patches speckling the image, with a large group of blurred Sandhill Cranes in the background. In the middle of the mass is the lone Yellow-headed Blackbird, the only one of his species in the group.⁠
⁠
Marti’s powerful image made this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

Restoring green spaces in urban habitats can have notable impacts on native species living there. It’s hard to believe this scenic spot used to be a landfill, but it’s become Blake Bryant’s (@blakewbphotos) favorite spot to birdwatch in Seattle. On one uniquely visible morning, he found six Double-crested Cormorants perched on exposed logs over the water.⁠
⁠
On average, the day would usually bring in the city’s infamous drizzle and overcast skies. But after months of visits, Blake found himself in the perfect photography conditions on this particular morning. The sunrise was visible against the morning fog and the water was at a level that exposed the perches rather than the underlying gravel bar—where, of course, the Double-crested Cormorants were drying their waterlogged wings after diving for breakfast. Encapsulated in a light fog, two of the silhouetted birds face each other and stretch their wings in the golden light.⁠
⁠
Blake’s mesmerizing shot was included in this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

A new report out yesterday from the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (@IPCC), the primary international body responsible for monitoring and responding to climate change, lays out in stark terms what birds and science have been telling us: the climate is changing rapidly, and we must reduce emissions to protect both birds and people. Addressing climate change should transcend ideology, and inspire bold, nonpartisan solutions from our leaders to respond to this undeniable threat.⁠
⁠
We must increase our use of renewable energy, support and add to landscapes that serve as natural infrastructure to reduce climate threats, and partner with stewards of our working lands to adopt practices that capture and store carbon naturally. Learn more via the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
A Hooded Warbler sits on a thin branch in a tree, with its beak open, singing. The image also shows Audubon's logo along with the hashtag #BirdsTellUs. 📷: Jesse R. Gordon (@jesse.r.gordon)/Audubon Photography Awards

node.text:
You’ll never forget the first time you photographed your favorite bird. Thanks to technology and social media, it’s easier than ever to learn its potential location from fellow birders in your city. For Alexander Eisengart (@kid_with_a_sony), that bird was an American Woodcock. According to eBird users in Cleveland, OH, there was one visiting a nearby cemetery. He headed there without delay.⁠
⁠
Ironically, the graveyard was teeming with life during this migration season. Only a few minutes after he found refuge in the green space, he found the woodcock, despite its camouflage. Alexander hid behind a tree and snapped several photos as it put on a show, flapping its wings as if to show off its beauty.⁠
⁠
The final image shows the American Woodcock, its outstretched wings high behind it, standing in brown fallen leaves that reflect its buff color. Its long bill points to the ground inprofile, with a blurred stone background lined with dead orange leaves behind it.⁠
⁠
Alexander’s spirited photo made this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

On #InternationalDayOfIndigenousPeoples, we celebrate the work of the Seal River Watershed Alliance—an Indigenous non-profit coalition aiming to permanently conserve the Seal River Watershed as an Indigenous Protected Area. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
To showcase the watershed’s importance to birds, the Seal River Watershed Alliance collaborated with our Boreal Conservation program. As part of this collaboration, Indigenous elders and youth from the Sayisi Dene First Nation deployed sound recording units by snowmobile across the still-frozen lakes to key locations in and around the Tadoule Lake area in Manitoba, Canada to help us understand which birds use critical breeding spots in the Boreal Forest. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Tap the link in our bio to learn more about their vital work and their project recording the sounds of a vital bird breeding area.⁠⁠
⁠⁠

When photographing in extreme weather conditions, it’s hard not to marvel at how adept creatures like the Great Gray Owl are at braving the elements. ❄️🦉⁠
⁠
Although he wore numerous layers of warm clothing, Scott Suriano (@sasphotography67) could only photograph for so long in the sub-zero temperatures of Northern Minnesota in January. But it was worth it when he saw this majestic owl rising from its roost on the frozen meadow, the light shimmering through its wingtips and tail feathers during its silent ascent. Once the owl perched, he continued to watch as it surveyed the landscape below. The freezing conditions were enough to make him quickly retreat back indoors, but the experience—and photograph—were their own rewards.⁠
⁠
The finished photo shows the Great Gray Owl flying from a frozen field to a bare branch. With its wings spread, the golden light from the emerging sunrise highlights its wingtips and tail feathers, adding a bit of warmth to this otherwise bluish scene.⁠
⁠
Scott’s stunning photograph was included in this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list. Tap the link in our bio to see the other 99.

node.text:
Have you got all your ducks in a row? 🦆 Kevin Sim (@kevinsimphotography) certainly did when he ventured to Assiniboine Park early one day to capture some birds in the morning sun.⁠
⁠
Sitting by the edge of a pond, he saw a dozen Wood Duck ducklings on top of a concrete island. One by one, each bird bravely jumped in and started swimming around. They came directly toward him in perfect alignment. He managed to get two shots before they got too close for the camera lens to focus, and he sincerely hoped that the ducklings would be sharp. He was overjoyed by what he saw when he popped the memory card into his computer.⁠
⁠
The finished shot shows three identical-looking ducklings swimming directly toward the camera, perfectly aligned from front to back, their orange-tipped blue beaks facing forward. The first duckling is the only one in focus, its reflection like a mirror in the dark green water in front of it. Small ripples make way on both of its sides.⁠
⁠
Kevin’s delightful photo made this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

node.text:
It’s a bird! It’s a plane! No! It’s—actually, we’re pretty sure it’s a bird after all.⁠
⁠
This elegant Violet-green Swallow could easily pass as a caped avian crusader, but it seemed content to fly calmly around Steve Hinch, who captured it amongst a massive mixed flock of Tree, Northern Rough-winged, and Cliff Swallows. As groups of them flew out over the sagebrush and Hebgen Lake to catch insects, they’d eventually land and rest near the dead tree where Steve had set up his equipment. This particular swallow sat by him briefly before it resumed hunting. ⁠
⁠
With its back to the camera, the vibrant green feathers on the top of the bird’s head and shoulders look like a cape, the color changing to a royal blue and purple bottom and gray wing and tail feathers.⁠
⁠
Steve’s flashy photo was selected to be in this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.

node.text:
For the first time since 1938, Piping Plovers are nesting in Ohio—and there are babies on board! 🐣⁠
⁠
Meet Nellie and her partner Nish, the first nesting pair of Piping Plovers in Ohio in 83 years. The pair made their home on the shores of Lake Erie in June, and recently became parents to a brood of four chicks on July 1st. It’s an optimistic sign of the critically endangered species’ return to the Great Lakes. Moreover, it’s evidence that #SharetheShore works. We applaud the work of volunteers from @bsbobird for educating the public on how they can protect the Piping Plover’s habitat and help prolong the survival of this cherished shorebird species.⁠
⁠
Get the details on Nish and Nellie’s backstory by tapping the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
Nish the Piping Plover attempts to court Nellie in Maumee Bay State Park, May, 2021. 📷: Christy Frank (@christylfrank)

Deliberately harming the planet might soon be tried as ‘ecocide’ in the International Criminal Court (ICC), the same international court that prosecutes war crimes and genocide. After years of deliberation, an international panel of lawyers released its first legal definition. ⁠
⁠
If added to the court’s statute and ratified, member states of the ICC could bring criminal charges to individuals—such as corporate CEOs and heads of state—for committing ecocide in their territories. It’s an important step in bringing accountability to some of the world’s biggest polluters. While enforcement is a long way off, the ratification could see hundreds of energy and fossil fuel companies recalibrate their strategies.⁠
⁠
To learn more about this effort to stop widespread environmental destruction, Audubon caught up with Jojo Mehta (@jojomehta), a co-founder of Stop Ecocide (@ecocidelaw), the organization leading this effort. Read the full interview by checking out the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
A Brown Pelican drenched in oil following the BP Deepwater Horizon oil spill, Louisiana, June, 2010. 📷: Charlie Riedel (@charlie_riedel_pix)/AP

node.text:
How do you outsmart one of the speediest birds? With plenty of free time on your hands and some ingenuity, of course.⁠
⁠
For decades, Adrienne Elliot has enjoyed watching a wide variety of birds in her yard, but always found it challenging to photograph them. This all changed during the COVID-19 lockdowns when she thought to attach some camouflage fabric to her sliding glass door and cut a hole for her camera lens. She also moved some of her feeders and added perches for the birds to land on. Since Downy Woodpeckers move so quickly, she was elated to get the shot.⁠
⁠
This shot shows a woodpecker perched on a branch that cuts across the frame horizontally, its black-and-white-striped back facing the camera. The bird’s body aligns perfectly with the branch. A red stripe across the back of its head stands out against a blurred beige background.⁠
⁠
Adrienne’s satisfying shot made this year’s #AudubonPhotographyAwards top 100 list.
